from collections import deque

def mostCompetitive(nums, k):
    stack = deque()
    n = len(nums)
    for i in range(n):
        while stack and stack[-1] > nums[i] and len(stack) + n - i > k:
            stack.pop()
        if len(stack) < k:
            stack.append(nums[i])
    return list(stack)
```


    The algorithm works by keeping a monotonically increasing stack. We iterate through the `nums` array and try to make our stack size equal to `k`. At each step, we check if it is possible to remove the current top element of the stack and still have `k` elements after processing all of the array elements. If it is possible and the current top element of the stack is greater than the current element in `nums`, we remove it. This ensures that the stack remains monotonically increasing and holds the most competitive subsequence of size `k`.

After processing all the elements in `nums`, the stack will have the most competitive subsequence of size `k`. We convert the stack into a result array/vector/list and return it.

